Here's an example of ClimateNet input channels and ground truth from out test set, and segmentation maps produced by our models.Tropical cyclones are green, atmospheric rivers yellow.You can see how our different models achieve higher recall for the classes of interest. https://t.co/xsIxrbIReN

More generally, we find that weighted losses lead to better recall (at the expense of lower precision).Moving along the precision-recall curve is desirable to minimize false negatives, given the high stakes and importance of not missing extreme weather events. https://t.co/fllppDd6YF

We find that the weighted Jaccard loss we introduce improves recall of tropical cyclones by +39.2% against the baseline CGnet implementation. (The baseline is itself a +41.6% IoU improvement over DeepLabv3+). https://t.co/RcUbeGWPcg

The key problem with extreme weather events is that they're rare by definition. Only ~0.5% of the pixels in our training set are tropical cyclones.We explore training on weighted loss functions to compensate for the inherent class imbalance -- and it works very well! https://t.co/W8YrRW2e8w

We train a light-weight context-guided network for semantic segmentation of tropical cyclones.CGNet uses chained 1x1 and 3x3 conv blocks to extract local features from context. With only ~500k parameters, CGnet is 99% smaller yet outperforms DeepLabv3+ and its ~50M params! https://t.co/XBJSyEtKbK

We work with ClimateNet, a fantastic open dataset of CAM5.1 climate simulation runs by @andregraubner @kapp_lukas and their co-authors.Climate scientist hand-labeled 451 simulation runs for tropical cyclones and atmospheric rivers. Each event is delineated by expert consensus. https://t.co/AFWvqkTF8A

In 2021, widespread crop damage occurred in Maharashtra due to unseasonal rainfall and hailstorms, affecting farmers in regions like Nashik, Satara, Sangli and Kolhapur. Heavy rains in parts of Karnataka caused landslides and flash floods, damaging crops.

In 2020 Cyclone Amphan hit West Bengal and Odisha, causing significant damage to crops like rice, coconut, and betel leaves.Farmers in Tamil Nadu suffered losses due to drought conditions, resulting in reduced yields of crops like sugarcane, paddy, and maize.

In 2020, heavy rains and floods in Bihar led to the inundation of farmland, causing significant crop damage,widespread locust attacks hit several states in India, including Rajasthan, Gujarat and Uttar Pradesh, damaging crops like wheat and mustard.

In 2019, unseasonal rain and hailstorms damaged crops in MP, affecting farmers in regions like Vidisha, Guna, and Ashok Nagar.In continuation, prolonged drought conditions in Maharashtra and Gujarat led to crop failures, forcing many farmers to migrate to other regions.

In 2018 Kerala Floods: Heavy rainfall and floods in Kerala led to the loss of crops and livelihoods for farmers.In 2019 Cyclone Fani: A severe cyclone hit the eastern coast of India, causing widespread damage to crops and infrastructure.

In 2015 Tamil Nadu Floods: Heavy rainfall and floods in Tamil Nadu led to crop failures and loss of livelihoods for farmers.In 2016 Haryana Drought: A severe drought hit the state of Haryana, leading to crop failures and farmer distress.

In 2009 Andhra Pradesh Drought: A severe drought hit the state of Andhra Pradesh, leading to crop failures and food shortages.In 2013 Uttarakhand Floods: Flash floods and landslides in Uttarakhand led to the loss of crops and livelihoods for farmers.

In 2002 Gujarat Drought: A prolonged drought hit the state of Gujarat, causing widespread crop failures and leading to farmer suicides. In 2005 Mumbai Floods: Heavy rainfall and floods in Mumbai led to the destruction of crops and loss of livelihoods for farmers.

1987 Drought: A severe drought affected large parts of India, leading to crop failures and food shortages. In 1998 Odisha Cyclone: A massive cyclone hit the eastern coast of India, causing widespread damage to crops and infrastructure.

The average building designer has a potentially thousand-fold greater impact on atmospheric carbon dioxide than the behavior of an average citizen over their lifetime.

In order to make our scarce resources for resilience go farther, we need to identify which infrastructure systems need to be hardened today vs. where we can take a wait-and-see approach to adapt our infrastructure as the climate changes.

We need science and engineering models to help us understand future demands on our infrastructure, help us design for increased demands, including adaptive features and help us quantify benefits relative to a status quo path.

We can no longer look at past performance of our infrastructure and say, ‚Äúwe want more of that.‚Äù Society increasingly has higher expectations for resilience, and systems that worked in the past will not work in the future.
